#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:10
msgid "1.2 The Boltzmann Distribution and Equilibrium"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:12
msgid ""
"Having established the analogy between magnetic spins and neural states, "
"we now turn to the central probabilistic law that governs such systems at"
" thermal equilibrium: the <b>Boltzmann distribution</b>. This "
"distribution provides the mathematical foundation for treating neural "
"networks as probabilistic generative models rather than merely "
"deterministic function approximators."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:14
msgid "<b>Thermal Equilibrium and the Canonical Ensemble</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:16
msgid ""
"Consider a physical system in contact with a large heat-bath at absolute "
"temperature $T$. The system constantly exchanges energy with the bath: "
"microscopic fluctuations push it into higher-energy configurations, while"
" the tendency to minimize energy pulls it back toward lower-energy "
"states. After sufficient time, the system reaches <b>thermal "
"equilibrium</b>, a condition in which macroscopic properties cease to "
"change, even though microscopic configurations continue to fluctuate."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:18
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"In the framework of statistical mechanics, an equilibrium system is "
"described by the <b>canonical ensemble</b>. The fundamental postulate is "
"that all microstates with the same energy are equally probable, and the "
"probability of the system occupying a specific microstate $\\mathbf{x}$ "
"with energy $E(\\mathbf{x})$ depends only on that energy and the "
"temperature. This dependence is expressed by the Boltzmann distribution."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:20
msgid "<b>The Boltzmann Distribution</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:22
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"The probability of finding the system in state $\\mathbf{x}$ at "
"temperature $T$ is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:24
msgid ""
"P(\\mathbf{x}) = \\frac{1}{Z} \\exp\\left(-\\frac{E(\\mathbf{x})}{k_B "
"T}\\right)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:26
msgid "where:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:28
#, python-brace-format
msgid "$E(\\mathbf{x})$ is the energy of configuration $\\mathbf{x}$."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:29
msgid ""
"$k_B$ is the Boltzmann constant, which bridges temperature and energy "
"scales."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:30
msgid "$T$ is the absolute temperature in Kelvin."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:31
msgid ""
"$Z$ is the <b>partition function</b> (from German <em>Zustandssumme</em>,"
" \"sum over states\")."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:33
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"The factor $\\exp(-E(\\mathbf{x})/k_B T)$ is called the <b>Boltzmann "
"factor.</b> The negative sign in the exponent ensures that configurations"
" with <em>lower energy</em> receive <em>higher probability</em>. The "
"temperature $T$ modulates the steepness of this preference: at low "
"temperatures, the distribution is sharply peaked around the lowest-energy"
" states; at high temperatures, the distribution flattens, assigning non-"
"negligible probability to a much broader range of configurations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:35
msgid ""
"<b>Statistical Physics Foundations: Derivation from the Microcanonical "
"Ensemble</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:37
msgid ""
"The Boltzmann distribution is not an arbitrary choice; it follows "
"directly from the microcanonical ensemble when a small system is placed "
"in contact with a large heat reservoir."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:39
msgid ""
"Consider a small system $\\mathcal{S}$ with energy eigenstates "
"$|i\\rangle$ and energies $E_i$, in thermal contact with a large "
"reservoir $\\mathcal{R}$ at temperature $T$. The combined system "
"$\\mathcal{S} + \\mathcal{R}$ is isolated, with total energy "
"$E_{\\text{total}}$. By the fundamental assumption of the microcanonical "
"ensemble, all microstates of the combined system with energy in the range"
" $(E_{\\text{total}}, E_{\\text{total}} + \\delta E)$ are equally "
"probable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:41
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"The number of microstates of the reservoir when $\\mathcal{S}$ is in "
"state $|i\\rangle$ is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:43
msgid ""
"\\Omega_R(E_{\\text{total}} - E_i) = \\exp\\left[ k^{-1} "
"S_R(E_{\\text{total}} - E_i) \\right]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:45
msgid ""
"Since $E_i \\ll E_{\\text{total}}$, we expand the entropy of the "
"reservoir:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:47
msgid ""
"S_R(E_{\\text{total}} - E_i) \\approx S_R(E_{\\text{total}}) - \\left( "
"\\frac{\\partial S_R}{\\partial E} \\right) E_i = S_R(E_{\\text{total}}) "
"- \\frac{1}{T} E_i"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:49
msgid "where we have used the thermodynamic definition of temperature:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:51
#, python-brace-format
msgid "\\frac{1}{T} = \\left( \\frac{\\partial S}{\\partial E} \\right)_{V,N}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:53
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"Thus, the probability that $\\mathcal{S}$ is in state $|i\\rangle$ is "
"proportional to the number of reservoir microstates:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:55
msgid ""
"P_i \\propto \\Omega_R(E_{\\text{total}} - E_i) \\propto \\exp\\left( "
"-\\frac{E_i}{k_B T} \\right)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:57
msgid ""
"Normalizing by the partition function $Z = \\sum_i \\exp(-E_i / k_B T)$ "
"yields the Boltzmann distribution."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:59
msgid ""
"This derivation reveals a crucial insight: <b>the temperature </b>$T$<b> "
"and the thermal noise in the Boltzmann machine are not arbitrary "
"heuristics; they emerge from the coupling of the neural system to an "
"external heat bath.</b> Stochasticity is a physical necessity for "
"maintaining thermal equilibrium."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:61
msgid "<b>The Partition Function: A Computational Bottleneck</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:63
msgid ""
"The partition function $Z$ is defined as the sum of Boltzmann factors "
"over all possible states:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:65
msgid ""
"Z = \\sum_{\\tilde{\\mathbf{x}}} "
"\\exp\\left(-\\frac{E(\\tilde{\\mathbf{x}})}{k_B T}\\right)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:67
msgid ""
"Its role is purely normalizing, it ensures that the probabilities over "
"all states sum to one:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:69
msgid ""
"\\sum_{\\tilde{\\mathbf{x}}} P(\\tilde{\\mathbf{x}}) = \\frac{1}{Z} "
"\\sum_{\\tilde{\\mathbf{x}}} "
"\\exp\\left(-\\frac{E(\\tilde{\\mathbf{x}})}{k_B T}\\right) = 1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:71
msgid ""
"While mathematically simple in definition, the partition function is "
"computationally formidable. For a system of $N$binary units, the sum runs"
" over $2^N$ distinct configurations. For even modest $N$(say, $N=100$, "
"this number exceeds the estimated number of atoms in the observable "
"universe. <b>The intractability of the partition function is the central "
"computational challenge</b> that shapes every aspect of Boltzmann machine"
" learning, from training algorithms to architectural constraints."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:73
msgid "<b>The Thermodynamic Limit and Ensemble Equivalence</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:75
msgid ""
"For a macroscopic system (large $N$), the canonical and microcanonical "
"ensembles become equivalent. This is because the energy fluctuations in "
"the canonical ensemble scale as:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:77
msgid "\\frac{\\Delta E}{\\langle E \\rangle} \\propto \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{N}}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:79
msgid ""
"which becomes negligible as $N \\to \\infty$. This is the "
"<b>thermodynamic limit</b>. In this limit, the energy of the system is "
"essentially fixed, and the canonical ensemble gives the same results as "
"the microcanonical ensemble."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:81
msgid ""
"This property is important for Boltzmann machines: when the number of "
"units is large, the model's equilibrium distribution is sharply peaked "
"around the mean energy, and the system behaves as if it were isolated "
"with a fixed energy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:83
msgid "<b>The Boltzmann Distribution in Neural Networks</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:85
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"Translating the physical expression into the language of neural networks "
"requires only a redefinition of variables. For a Boltzmann machine with "
"binary units $\\mathbf{x} \\in \\{0,1\\}^N$ (or equivalently "
"$\\{-1,+1\\}^N$), we absorb the Boltzmann constant into the temperature "
"parameter and define the <b>energy function</b> $E_\\theta(\\mathbf{x})$ "
"parameterized by biases $\\mathbf{b}$ and symmetric weights "
"$\\mathbf{W}$:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:87
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"P_\\theta(\\mathbf{x}) = \\frac{1}{Z_\\theta} "
"\\exp\\left(-E_\\theta(\\mathbf{x})\\right)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:89
msgid "where the partition function becomes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:91
msgid ""
"Z_\\theta = \\sum_{\\tilde{\\mathbf{x}}} "
"\\exp\\left(-E_\\theta(\\tilde{\\mathbf{x}})\\right)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:93
msgid "and the energy is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:95
#, python-brace-format
msgid "E_\\theta(\\mathbf{x}) = -\\sum_i b_i x_i - \\sum_{i<j} w_{ij} x_i x_j"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:97
msgid ""
"Here we have set $k_B T = 1$ for notational simplicity; the temperature "
"can be reintroduced as a scaling factor on the energy or, equivalently, "
"as an inverse temperature parameter $\\beta = 1/T$. In practice, the "
"temperature is often treated as a hyperparameter controlling the "
"stochasticity of sampling."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:99
msgid "<b>The Meaning of Equilibrium in a Neural Context</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:101
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"When we say a Boltzmann machine samples from its <b>equilibrium "
"distribution</b>, we mean that after running the stochastic update "
"dynamics for a sufficiently long time, the probability of observing any "
"particular configuration $\\mathbf{x}$ converges to "
"$P_\\theta(\\mathbf{x})$. This property is guaranteed by the fact that "
"the update rule satisfies <b>detailed balance, </b>a condition ensuring "
"that, in equilibrium, the flow of probability from state $\\mathbf{x}$ to"
" state $\\mathbf{x}'$ exactly balances the reverse flow:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:103
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"P_\\theta(\\mathbf{x}) \\, P(\\mathbf{x} \\to \\mathbf{x}') = "
"P_\\theta(\\mathbf{x}') \\, P(\\mathbf{x}' \\to \\mathbf{x})"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:105
msgid "The stochastic neuron update rule introduced earlier,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:107
#, python-brace-format
msgid "P(x_i = 1) = \\sigma\\left( \\sum_j w_{ij} x_j + b_i \\right)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:109
msgid ""
"where $\\sigma(z) = 1/(1+\\exp(-z))$, is precisely designed to satisfy "
"detailed balance with respect to the energy function $E_\\theta$. "
"Consequently, if we run the network long enough, which allowing it to "
"\"forget\" its initial state, the configurations it generates will be "
"distributed according to $P_\\theta$."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:111
msgid "<b>From Physics to Learning</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:113
msgid ""
"The Boltzmann distribution reframes the learning problem in probabilistic"
" terms. Instead of asking \"how do we compute a function from inputs to "
"outputs?\", we ask <b>\"how do we adjust the parameters </b>$\\theta$<b> "
"so that the equilibrium distribution </b>$P_\\theta$<b> matches the "
"empirical distribution of the observed data?\"</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:115
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"This shift in perspective is profound. The energy function "
"$E_\\theta(\\mathbf{x})$ becomes a <b>scoring function</b>: data points "
"that are typical of the training set should be assigned low energy (high "
"probability), while atypical or impossible configurations should reside "
"at high energy (low probability). Learning, then, consists of "
"<b>sculpting the energy landscape</b> by adjusting the weights and biases"
" so that the valleys of low energy coincide with regions of high data "
"density."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:117
msgid ""
"The challenge, as we shall see, lies in estimating how the partition "
"function $Z_\\theta$ changes as we modify the parameters. Because "
"$Z_\\theta$ depends on all $2^N$ states, we cannot compute it, or its "
"gradient exactly. The remainder of this tutorial series is, in large "
"measure, a study of how to circumvent this intractability through clever "
"sampling techniques and architectural restrictions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:119
msgid "<b>Summary</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:121
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"The <b>Boltzmann distribution</b>$P(\\mathbf{x}) \\propto "
"\\exp(-E(\\mathbf{x})/T)$emerges naturally at thermal equilibrium and "
"forms the probabilistic core of the Boltzmann machine."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:122
msgid ""
"The <b>partition function </b>$Z$normalizes the distribution but requires"
" summing over an exponential number of states, making exact computation "
"infeasible for large systems."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:123
msgid ""
"In neural terms, <b>equilibrium</b> means the network's stochastic "
"dynamics have converged to a stationary distribution defined by its "
"weights and biases."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:124
msgid ""
"Learning in a Boltzmann machine is equivalent to <b>energy landscape "
"shaping</b>: lowering the energy of observed data configurations while "
"implicitly raising the energy elsewhere."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-boltzmann.md:125
msgid ""
"The intractability of $Z$ motivates the development of approximate "
"inference and learning algorithms, which will be explored in subsequent "
"sections."
msgstr ""

